<li class=" comment" id="comment-55875">
	<div id="div-comment-55875">
		<div class="comment_meta">
			<span class="comment_author">Mark</span>
			<br />
			<span class="comment_time">
				November 14th, 2009				<br />
				<a href="#comment-55875" alt="Permalink to this comment">8:14 pm</a>
			</span>
			<br />
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/30e9b94cb73b4c3e8366219c89441a07?s=64&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-64 photo' height='64' width='64' />		</div>
		<div class="comment_entry">
			<p>Ok I have a cooking hack for you. I discovered this one myself.</p>
<p>Ever overcooked some rice until it&#8217;s mushy and will mostly turn into goop when you strain it?</p>
<p>Next time this happens, instead of straining it like normal get your pan and fill it as quick as possible with cold water. Very quickly give the water and rice a stir round a couple of times and then strain it as fast as possible. They key is to be quick so the rice stays hot enough to eat and remaining water will evaporate.</p>
<p>Essentially you are using the cold water to wash away the really overcooked mushy parts of the rice and leave the bits that are just about edible behind. Not as good as cooking it properly but saves you have to throw it away and make another batch. This has saved my butt many times (I perpetually overcook rice for some reason).</p>
<p>Viola!</p>
					</div>
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/blog/2008/07/02/how-to-peel-hard-boiled-eggs-without-peeling/?replytocom=55875#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-55875", "55875", "respond", "378")'>Reply</a>	</div>
